<font color="#FF0000">PTSD</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 11 15:32:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This may sound odd, but I am glad that I have PTSD.<br><br>
Now I know why I have been messed up for the past 27 years!<br><br>
All the &quot;black and white&quot; and &quot;5 second decisions&quot;, rage, dissociation, fear, panic, isolation, claustrophobia, fear of crowds, always sitting in the back of a room, my back always to a wall, feeling trapped, and all the rest of that seemingly illogical behavior now makes perfect sense. <br><br>
Understanding it is only part of the control. It really takes hard work to bring some of this stuff into a manageable range, and then sometimes medication only works.<br><br>
The 4th of July fireworks stuff has always been bad. Last year I really tripped out and went looking for a place to hide. This year I decided that I was going to have some fun, so I went with friends who are familiar with my problem,<br>
brought along my meds and wound up taking some, got real close but did not go over the edge, and had what passed as fun of sorts. That was an improvement!<br><br>
After classes in PTSD and anger management, and continuing psychological therapy, I find myself with five guys my age and who are just like me, in a trauma processing group. The next step.<br><br>
I am really scared. I haven't yet looked some of this stuff in the eye. I am also really motivated. This thing almost got me last summer. The emerging &quot;me&quot; will be in control. I know I will slip, as I have in the past, but it is two steps forward for every one step back! <br><br>
It is just plain hard work, and wanting to do it. <br><br>
Frank, I like your poem. Short and sweet, and it says a lot.
